    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-11-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-11-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="43"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d43">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/700.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Extracts.—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-11-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 27, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I report with reserve that the Legation has been requested by the Chinese
                    Government to inform the Department that the Japanese <pb facs="0170" n="54"
                        xml:id="pg_54"/> are supplying revolutionists in South Manchuria railway
                    zone with funds for arms and recruits and are giving them free passage on
                    trains. Four Japanese are advisers to revolutionists. Japanese also reported
                    arming Hunghutzus. The Viceroy addressed the Japanese Consul General out
                    obtained no satisfaction.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Calhoun.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
